{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a86a67c5-5f27-430c-ae1e-f836de49d1fa","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the **`webapi`** template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n### Authentication options (`--auth`):\n\n| Value | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No authentication (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n### Example with auth:\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --client-id <app-id> --tenant-id <tenant-id>\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` if you need a custom identity provider. Want me to scaffold a project with a specific auth option?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"736bce00-42d7-4fdb-9c6d-777f5f117050","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.","outputTokens":272,"requestId":"A7E4:7A682:1585875:180FFFA:6A051DAF"},"id":"72dabdc0-dfca-4cc9-881e-a0c51e07ad2c","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:56:27.682Z","parentId":"0f1c8689-1528-4150-afcb-71522ffbd34e"}
